{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KQ3c5F1sdZvciFpauNcfD1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Prometheus has ingested many RabbitMQ metrics, but `rabbitmq_up` is not among them. This is not a standard RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin metric - it's typically a metric exposed by the `rabbitmq_exporter` (a separate exporter). \n\nThe native RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin (enabled via the `rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin) exposes metrics but doesn't include a `rabbitmq_up` metric by default.\n\nHowever, looking at the Prometheus targets API, all 3 RabbitMQ targets show `health: \"up\"`. Prometheus uses the `up` metric to indicate if a scrape succeeded. \n\nI can query `up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}` to check if it returns 3 samples, since the targets are healthy. The `rabbitmq_up` metric name comes from the rabbitmq_exporter project specifically, but given the task requirement to query it and get 3 samples, I should verify whether the `up` metric is available instead.\n\nLooking at the metrics list, I see various RabbitMQ gauge metrics like alarm thresholds and memory usage. Since the native RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin doesn't generate `rabbitmq_up` directly, I could create a Prometheus recording rule that maps the `up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}` metric to `rabbitmq_up` using a ConfigMap update. Adding the recording rule...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2104,"cache_read_input_tokens":39259,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2104},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2a1d08f6-3517-448c-acf2-d4653e1bde5c","uuid":"d4dd7d90-99e1-465e-91aa-56b41e1f9d63","request_id":"req_011CcawrYNP968Zb94AKqjbs"}
