{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LSQGBXAstqXTPUcPrKskPu","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All requirements are met. Here's a summary of what was done:\n\n**Problem:** The `prometheus-config` ConfigMap only contained a self-scrape job (`localhost:9090`) with no RabbitMQ targets.\n\n**Fix — two changes to the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap:**\n\n1. **Added a `rabbitmq` scrape job** targeting all 3 pods by their headless-service DNS names (`rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local:15692`). Using the headless service is the correct approach — it gives stable per-pod DNS names without needing a load-balancer.\n\n2. **Added a recording rule** `rabbitmq_up = up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}` in a `rules.yml` key. The native RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin doesn't emit `rabbitmq_up`; Prometheus's synthetic `up` metric carries the same information, so the recording rule bridges the gap.\n\nAfter restarting the Prometheus deployment to pick up the new ConfigMap:\n- **3 RabbitMQ targets show `health: \"up\"`** in `/api/v1/targets`\n- **`rabbitmq_up` returns 3 samples**, each with value `1`\n- **All 3 RabbitMQ pods remain healthy** (`1/1 Running`)"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":755,"cache_read_input_tokens":44830,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":755},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2a1d08f6-3517-448c-acf2-d4653e1bde5c","uuid":"bfad5829-f672-4e06-9d49-1c0c2bd146f5","request_id":"req_011Ccax1nMWa2W2HyYTe3sKe"}
